The 16th Division had a considerable number of gas casualties during the German attacks; the greatest number of deaths occurred, at the points on the British front where the gas was most concentrated. Anti-gas blankets fitted on dug-out entrances were found to be ineffective but Lewis-guns wrapped in blankets and sprayed with Vermorel during the passage of the gas cloud, were only slightly affected. Some ammunition was made unusable and some rifles jammed, due to chemical deposits forming on the bolts. The troops most affected by the gas could not be relieved immediately but were exempted from carrying duties for the next day and no ill-effects were reported. British troops were said to have been greatly encouraged by the German fiasco but uneasy about the protection offered by their PH gas helmets. The troops were deceived, by being told that the helmets issued to the 16th Division, had not been properly impregnated with chemical neutralisers and that 16th Division gas discipline had been unsatisfactory.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|pp=196–197}} New "box respirators", worn by Lewis gunners, were found to have worked well and production was expedited.{{sfn|Fries|West|1921|pp=198–200}}

===Casualties===
On 27 April the 16th Division had lost {{nowrap|442 men}} and the 15th Division reported {{nowrap|107 losses.}}{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|p=195}} Total British casualties from {{nowrap|27–29 April}} were {{nowrap|1,980, of}} whom {{nowrap|1,260 were}} gas casualties, {{nowrap|338 being}} killed.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|p=196}}{{efn|The 7th [[Royal Irish Fusiliers]]: {{nowrap|80 gas}} casualties, 7th [[Royal Inniskilling Fusiliers]]: {{nowrap|263 gas}} casualties, 8th Royal Inniskilling Fusiliers: {{nowrap|366 gas}} casualties ({{nowrap|73 percent}}) 8th [[Royal Dublin Fusiliers]]: {{nowrap|385 gas}} casualties and wounded, ({{nowrap|c. 50 percent}}) about two-thirds of the casualties being due to gas. More than {{nowrap|900 of}} the {{nowrap|1,260 gas}} casualties were incurred by these battalions.{{sfn|MacPherson|Herringham|Elliott|Balfour|1923|p=284}}}} German casualties in BIR 5, BRIR 5, PR 36 who operated the gas cylinders and other non-infantry troops were not known in 1932, when the British Official History was published. BIR 9 had {{nowrap|419 casualties,}} {{nowrap|286 from}} gas, of whom {{nowrap|163 died}} and there were {{nowrap|34 more}} gas casualties in the 3rd Bavarian Division, of whom four men died.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|p=198}} A contemporary French intelligence summary recorded {{nowrap|1,100 casualties}} in the 4th Bavarian Division from {{nowrap|27–29 April}} and in October 1918, an officer of the British 15th Division found the graves of {{nowrap|400 German}} gas casualties at the cemetery at Pont-à-Vendin, from the gas discharges.{{sfn|US WD|1920|p=102}}{{sfn|Stewart|Buchan|2003|p=68}} In 1934, Foulkes wrote that a diary taken from a captured soldier of the 4th Bavarian Division, recorded {{nowrap|1,600 gas}} casualties in the division and in 2002, Hook and Jones recorded {{nowrap|1,500 casualties}} from the German gas which blew back on 29 April.{{sfn|Foulkes|1934|p=118}}{{sfn|Hook|Jones|2002|p=22}}{{efn|Hook and Jones also wrote that the Pioneers wore an improved {{lang|de|''Rahmenmaske''}} but had little time to put them on and that many of the masks of the Bavarian infantry were in poor condition; the writers offered no sources.{{sfn|Hook|Jones|2002|p=22}}}}

